{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488266"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:35:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:35:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"398"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/398"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.39,0.08,0.03,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/398"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47026"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"1056"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of intermittent burning pain in her right hand. The symptoms occasionally wake her at night and are associated with numbness and tingling in the hand. She also notes that the symptoms are worse after work as a supermarket worker. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and osteoarthritis of the knees. Her medications include metformin and paracetamol. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The musculoskeletal examination of her hand and wrist is normal, except for reproduction of her symptoms when full flexion is applied to her wrist for 60 seconds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI of the cervical spine","Ultrasound of the wrist","HbA1c","Plain X-rays of the cervical spine","Nerve conduction studies"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are strongly suggestive of carpal tunnel syndrome. The diagnosis is supported by a positive Phalen\u0027s test on examination (reproduction of symptoms on full flexion of the wrist for 60 seconds). While the diagnosis is primarily clinical, \u003Cstrong\u003Enerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate initial investigation in this case for several reasons:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. They provide objective evidence of median nerve compression at the wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. They help establish the severity of the neuropathy, which is crucial for treatment planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. They can help predict the potential benefit of surgical intervention, as patients with middle-range findings tend to benefit more from surgery compared to those with very severe or very mild findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. They can be useful in cases with atypical presentations or when considering differential diagnoses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the wrist\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used as an initial diagnostic tool for carpal tunnel syndrome. While it can visualize the median nerve and surrounding structures, it is less informative than nerve conduction studies for assessing nerve function and severity of compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHbA1c\u003C/strong\u003E is important for monitoring this patient\u0027s diabetes control but is not directly relevant to the diagnosis or management of her carpal tunnel symptoms. While diabetes is a risk factor for carpal tunnel syndrome, assessing glycemic control would not be the most appropriate initial investigation for her presenting complaint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain X-rays of the cervical spine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the cervical spine\u003C/strong\u003E are used to investigate cervical radiculopathy, which can present with similar symptoms to carpal tunnel syndrome. However, in this case, there are no clinical features suggesting that her symptoms are arising from her neck. The distribution of symptoms (limited to the hand) and the positive Phalen\u0027s test are more consistent with carpal tunnel syndrome than cervical radiculopathy. Therefore, these imaging studies are not necessary as the initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, nerve conduction studies are the most appropriate initial investigation as they provide objective evidence of median nerve compression, help determine the severity of the condition, and guide management decisions, including the potential benefit of surgical intervention such as carpal tunnel release.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nerve conduction studies in carpal tunnel syndrome help determine severity and guide management decisions, including the potential benefit of surgical intervention.","Clinical diagnosis of carpal tunnel syndrome is based on characteristic symptoms and physical examination findings, such as the Phalen\u0027s test.","Carpal tunnel syndrome can be associated with conditions like diabetes and osteoarthritis."],"references":["Middleton SD, Anakwe RE. Carpal tunnel syndrome. BMJ. 2014;349:g6437. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g6437.long"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47026"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47026"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T20:41:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T20:41:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"398"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61573"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationship